note: The output has "provenance-string" injected inside the "ietf-green:sources" object.

mpalmero@mac provenance % curl -k -X POST 'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-verifier'  --data-binary "@source_signed.json"
Signature verified


The source-id ("router-edge-01") is inside the signed bytes. The controller verifies it, gets Signature verified, and sets traceability-verified = true in the YANG datastore next to that source entry. If anyone changes the id, power-watts, or any other field after signing, verification fails and the controller sets traceability-verified = false.


**Method 2 — notification  (YANG-Push streaming scenario)**

Wraps the source entry inside a YANG-Push event. This is the scenario where the controller subscribes to source-status updates and receives them as streaming notifications. The key must be exactly "ietf-yp-notification:envelope".


mpalmero@mac provenance % more source_notification.json 
{
  "ietf-yp-notification:envelope": {
    "eventTime": "2024-02-03T11:22:41Z",
    "ietf-yang-push:push-update": {
      "id": 1,
      "datastore-contents": {
        "ietf-green:sources": {
          "source": [
            {
              "id": "router-edge-01",
              "mechanisms": [ "cose-provenance" ],
              "timestamp": "2024-02-03T11:22:41Z",
              "location": "datacenter-madrid-01",
              "energy-metrics": {
                "power-watts": 187.4,
                "throughput-gbps": 38.2,
                "efficiency-gbps-per-watt": 0.204
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}


